{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20161224180939|756499104","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"John_Fleming_(American_politician)","to":"John Fleming (American politician)"}],"pages":{"20334913":{"pageid":20334913,"ns":0,"title":"John Fleming (American politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2016-12-30T21:22:29Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = John Calvin Fleming, Jr.\n|image       = John flemming.jpg\n|state       = [[Louisiana]]\n|district    = {{ushr|LA|4|4th}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 2009\n|term_end    = <!--January 3, 2017-->\n|predecessor = [[Jim McCrery]]\n|successor   = [[Mike Johnson (Louisiana politician)|Mike Johnson]] <small>(elect)</small>\n|birth_name  = John Calvin Fleming, Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1951|7|5}}\n|birth_place = [[Meridian, Mississippi|Meridian]], [[Mississippi]], USA\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|resting_place=\n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Cindy\n|children    = Four children\n|alma_mater  = [[University of Mississippi|University of Mississippi, Oxford]]<br>[[University of Mississippi Medical Center|University of Mississippi, Jackson]]\n|religion    = [[Southern Baptist Convention|Southern Baptist]]<ref name=Baptist>{{cite news |url=http://www.bpnews.net/bpnews.asp?id=34378 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226010629/http://www.bpnews.net/34378 |title=Ten Southern Baptists sworn in as new reps. |last=Staff |date=January 5, 2011 |newspaper=Baptist Press |accessdate=September 4, 2013 |archivedate=December 26, 2014}}</ref>\n|allegiance  = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch      = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n}}\n'''John Calvin Fleming, Jr.''' (born July 5, 1951), is an [[United States|American]] [[politician]], [[physician]], and [[business]]man who has served as the [[U.S. Representative]] for [[Louisiana's 4th congressional district]] since 2009. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], he lives in his adopted city of [[Minden, Louisiana|Minden]] in [[Webster Parish, Louisiana|Webster Parish]] in northwestern [[Louisiana]]. He vacates his position on January 3, 2017.\n\nA second cousin (five generations removed) to the former [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House of Representatives]] [[Henry Clay]] of [[Kentucky]], Fleming is a member of [[Sons of the American Revolution]] and [[Jamestowne Society]]; he is only the second Republican to hold his House seat since [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]].\n\n==Early life, education and family==\nFleming was born in [[Meridian, Mississippi|Meridian]] in [[Lauderdale County, Mississippi|Lauderdale County]] in  eastern [[Mississippi]]. He was reared in a working class home in which his mother became disabled and could not work when he was still young. Just prior to his high school graduation, Fleming's father died of a [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]], and young Fleming had to work his way through college. He attended the [[University of Mississippi]] in [[Oxford, MS]], where he was a member of the [[Phi Delta Theta Fraternity]]. Fleming was awarded his [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in 1973. He went on to attend medical school at the same university, but at the [[Jackson, Mississippi|Jackson]] campus and received his [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] degree in 1976.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rep. John Fleming|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/almanac/2010/person/john-fleming-la/|publisher=National Journal Almanac|accessdate=April 15, 2013}}</ref> He entered the [[United States Navy]] to continue his medical training in 1976 and served until 1982 after completing his residency in 1979. Fleming also trained for years in karate attaining the rank of third degree black belt.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=November 22, 2008|url=http://www.johncfleming.com/articles-physicianSpotlight.php|title=Physician Spotlight: John C. Fleming|first=Patricia |last=Gannon |date=September 2007 |publisher=LouisianaMedialNews.com}}</ref> Fleming and his wife, Cindy, married in 1978. The couple has four children.<ref name=MeridianStar_Brown_20070627/>\n\n==Medical career==\nAfter earning his medical degree, Fleming was chief resident in [[family medicine]] at the Naval Regional Medical Center in [[Camp Pendleton, California]]. He also trained at the drug and alcohol treatment unit at the Navy Regional Medical Center in [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]], California.<ref name=MeridianStar_Brown_20070627>{{cite news|accessdate=November 22, 2008|url=http://www.meridianstar.com/local/local_story_178002646.html|date=June 27, 2007|title=Meridian native named Family Doctor of Year|first=Ida |last=Brown |work=The Meridian Star}}</ref> Serving in the Navy after his residency, Fleming practiced family medicine on the island of [[Guam]].<ref>''[[Minden Press-Herald]]'', November 18, 1982, p. 14</ref> From 1979 to 1981, he was the director of drug and alcohol treatment and chairman of the Navy Family Advocacy Committee. He subsequently performed similar duties in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]], [[South Carolina]].<ref name=MeridianStar_Brown_20070627/>\n\nAfter leaving the Navy, Fleming established his practice in Minden in August 1982. His first clinic was on Pearl Street across from the [[United States Post Office]]. He chose Minden for his city of residence because, in his words, it \"has small-town charm, warm essence of life, long, lazy summer days with watermelon cuts and family reunions.\"<ref>''Minden Press-Herald'', August 10, 1982, p. 1</ref> To attract patients to his new practice, Fleming announced evening and Saturday morning hours to accommodate working people and students.<ref>''Minden Press-Herald'', September 2, 1982, p. 10</ref>\n\nFleming received a certification from the American Board of Family Practice<ref name=MeridianStar_Brown_20070627/> and joined the staff of the Minden Medical Center.<ref name=MindenHospital_Staff>{{cite web|accessdate=November 23, 2008|url=http://wayback.archive.org/web/20090302135059/http://www.mindenmedicalcenter.com/news/?page_id=18|title=Physicians |publisher=Minden Medical Center}}</ref> Fleming also joined the Louisiana Academy of Family Physicians (LAFP). In 2007, he was chosen as the LAFP \"Louisiana Family Practice Physician of the Year.\"<ref name=\"MeridianStar_Brown_20070627\"/>\n\nFleming previously worked with chemically dependent persons through the program called \"New Beginnings\" at the Minden Medical Center.<ref>\"Dr. Fleming will help chemical dependents\", ''Minden Press-Herald'', October 18, 1987, p. 10</ref> In 1994, the ''[[Minden Press-Herald]]'' revealed Dr. Fleming's call \"to end violence and drug addiction. I link these two together because I believe most of the violence we see is caused by addiction to or buying and selling of drugs.\"<ref>Fannie Moore, \"Citizens list top priorities for 1994\", ''Minden Press-Herald'', January 6, 1994, p. 1.</ref> Fleming's book, ''Preventing Addiction: What Parents Must Know to Immunize Their Kids Against Drug And Alcohol Addiction'' was published in 2006.<ref>Fleming, John C. (2006). [http://books.google.ca/books?id=xblJhwtj6A8C ''Preventing Addiction: What Parents Must Know to Immunize Their Kids Against Drug And Alcohol Addiction'']. Hannibal Books:A Christian Evangelical Publishing Company. [[Garland, Texas|Garland]], [[Texas]]. ISBN 0929292456</ref>\n\n==Business career==\nFleming is a businessman who owns thirty-six [[Subway (restaurant)|Subway sandwich shops]] in North Louisiana<ref name=mph/><ref name=Politico_Kraushaar_20081117>{{cite web|accessdate=November 22, 2008|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1108/15697.html|title=GOP fights to hold onto Louisiana seat|first=Josh|last=Kraushaar|date=November 11, 2008|work=Politico}}</ref> and Fleming Expansions, LLC, a regional developer for [[United Parcel Service|The UPS Store]], with outlets in Louisiana, Mississippi and Texas.<ref name=mph>{{cite news|accessdate=November 24, 2008|title=Minden's Fleming running for Congress|work=[[Minden Press-Herald]]|date=January 18, 2008|page=1|url=http://www.nwlanews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7391&Itemid=1}}{{dead link|date=April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Webster Parish coroner==\nIn 1987, Fleming entered the race for Webster Parish [[coroner]] against the incumbent, the late Dr. Charles Hancock, but withdrew after learning the position would take too much time from his regular medical duties.<ref>\"Dr. Fleming exits race for coroner\", ''Minden Press-Herald'', October 1, 1987, p. 1</ref>\n\nIn 1995, he ran for coroner again. He defeated the [[nonpartisan]] candidate, Dr. Carlos A. Irizarry, 7,842 votes (60.4 percent) to 5,143 (39.6 percent). Fleming succeeded [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[incumbent]] Dr. Carl A. Hines, from Minden, who did not seek re-election.<ref name=Politico_Kraushaar_20081117/><ref name=ElectionResults_19951021>{{cite web|publisher=Louisiana Secretary of State|work=Official Parish Election Results|title=Results for Election Date: 10/21/95 \u2013 Parish of Webster|url= http://www400.sos.louisiana.gov:8090/cgibin/?rqstyp=elcpr&rqsdta=10219560}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2008====\nFleming entered the race for the District 4 House seat after the 21-year Republican incumbent [[Jim McCrery]] announced his retirement from the House. Fleming received political support from the LAFP and the American Academy of Family Physicians' (AAFP) [[political action committee]] for his campaign.<ref name=LAFP_support>{{cite web|accessdate=November 22, 2008|url=http://www.lafp.org/index.htm|title=John Fleming, MD, Wins the Republican Nomination for 4th Congressional District|author=Submitted by Fleming for Congress |publisher=Louisiana Academy of Family Physicians|quote=On Friday, October 31, Dr. Roberts, LAFP Past President, presented Dr. Fleming with a check from FamMedPac, the AAFP's Political Action Committee. 'We were honored to receive another check from FamMedPac. I have received lots of support from fellow physicians, and I want to sincerely thank each one who has helped my campaign.'}}</ref>\n\nFleming supported the [[FairTax]],<ref name=mph/> which would replace the [[income tax]] with a flat rate on consumption, as defined in the legislation, of 23 percent of the total payment on personal consumption.<ref name=Money_Regnier_20060907>{{cite news| url=http://money.cnn.com/2005/09/06/pf/taxes/consumptiontax_0510/| last=Regnier| first=Pat| title=Just how fair is the FairTax?| work=Money Magazine| date=September 7, 2005| accessdate=September 24, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn the October 4, 2008, Republican [[closed primary]], Fleming ran against [[Jeff R. Thompson]], a lawyer from Bossier City, and Chris Gorman.{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}} In the election, no candidate received a majority of the votes. Fleming led with 14,500 votes (35.1 percent), followed by Gorman with 14,072 votes (34.1 percent), and Thompson with 12,693 votes (30.8 percent).<ref name=ElectionResults_20081004>{{cite web|publisher=Louisiana Secretary of State|work=Official Election Results|title=Results for Election Date: 10/04/08,|url=http://www400.sos.louisiana.gov:8090/cgibin/?rqstyp=elcms2&rqsdta=100408}}</ref> This established a primary [[runoff election|runoff]] between Fleming and Gorman. In the runoff, Fleming defeated Gorman, 43,012 votes (55.6 percent) to 34,405 (44.4 percent) and carried all but one of the thirteen parishes in the district.<ref name=\"Election Results_20081104\">{{cite web|publisher=Louisiana Secretary of State|work=Official Election Results|title=Results for Election Date: 11/04/08|format=See primary returns for Fourth Congressional District|url=http://www400.sos.louisiana.gov:8090/cgibin/?rqstyp=elcms2&rqsdta=110408}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2006 race against McCrery, \"Catfish\" Kelley ran as a Republican and drew 12 percent of the vote under the old primary format.<ref name=ElectionResults_20061107>{{cite web|publisher=Louisiana Secretary of State|work=Official Election Results|title=Results for Election Date: 11/07/06|url=http://www400.sos.louisiana.gov:8090/cgibin/?rqstyp=elcms2&rqsdta=110706}}</ref> In 2008, his 3 percent was far more than the margin between Fleming and Carmouche. A [[Plurality (voting)|plurality]] is sufficient to win the general election\u2014which, along with the [[Louisiana's 2nd congressional district|District 2]] race, were the last congressional races in the nation in 2008.<ref name=CQPolitics_20081111>{{cite news|accessdate=November 24, 2008 |url=http://www.cqpolitics.com/wmspage.cfm?docID=news-000002984888 |work=CQ Politics |date=November 11, 2008 |title=Still Some Undecided Races, But Obama Gets Electoral Grace Note in Nebraska |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081128025722/http://www.cqpolitics.com/wmspage.cfm?docID=news-000002984888 |archivedate=November 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOutgoing [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Dick Cheney]] appeared in Shreveport on November 21 to speak at a fundraiser for Fleming.<ref name=ShreveportTimes_Prine_20081122>{{cite news|first=John Andrew |last=Prine |title= Cheney boosts Fleming's campaign|work=[[The Times (Shreveport)|Shreveport Times]]|date=November 22, 2008 |url=http://www.shreveporttimes.com/article/20081122/ELECTION/811220331&referrer=FRONTPAGECAROUSEL |accessdate= November 22, 2008}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Politico.com indicated that McCrery supports Fleming but had made no official endorsement and had not appeared at any of Fleming's campaign events.<ref name=Politico_Kraushaar_20081117/> On December 2, McCrery spoke on Fleming's behalf in an appearance on ''[[Moon Griffon|The Moon Griffon Show]]'' radio program, which is syndicated in most Louisiana media markets. He used the argument that Carmouche, if successful, would cast his first vote for Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] of California.<ref>''[[Moon Griffon|The Moon Griffon Show]]'', syndicated radio program, December 2, 2008</ref>\n\nOn December 10, 2008, Paul Carmouche formally conceded the election to Fleming.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/scorecard/1208/Carmouche_concedes_to_Fleming.html?showall |accessdate=December 11, 2008 | title=Carmouche concedes to Fleming | first=Josh | last=Kraushaar | work=Politico | date=December 10, 2008}}</ref> Among the Democrats whom Carmouche defeated in his primary was later [[Louisiana State Senate|State Senator]] [[John Milkovich]] of Shreveport.\n\n====2010====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Louisiana, 2010#District 4}}\nFleming was unopposed in the Republican primary in 2010 but was challenged by the Democratic nominee, David R. Melville. [[governor of Louisiana|Governor]] [[Buddy Roemer]], then still a Republican and later a candidate for the 2012 Republican presidential nomination, supported David Melville in the general election.<ref>KEEL Radio News, October 11, 2010</ref>\n\nFleming was reelected saying that Democratic policies were out of step with his district and most of America.<ref>\"[http://www.ksla.com/Global/story.asp?S=13433540 Republican John Fleming re-elected for Congress]\" [[KSLA]] News, November 2, 2010. Retrieved December 29, 2010.</ref><ref>{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329152841/http://projects.usatoday.com/news/politics/2010/elections/LA/ |date=March 29, 2012 |title=\"Elections 2010:Louisiana\" }}</ref>\n\n====2012====\nFleming was unopposed by a Democratic candidate in his 2012 re-election bid in his district that is 2 to 1 Democratic registration but has a Cook PVI of R +11. In the November 6, 2012 general election, Fleming instead faced opposition from a [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] candidate, Randall Lord of Shreveport, a former chiropractor studying psychology at [[Louisiana State University in Shreveport]].<ref>Bonnie Culverhouse, \"Final candidate roster\", ''Minden Press-Herald'', August 20, 2012</ref> Fleming defeated Lord, 187,790 (75.3 percent) to 61,587 (24.7 percent).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/11062012/11062012_Congressional.html|title=Louisiana election returns, November 6, 2012|publisher=staticresults.sos.la.gov|accessdate=November 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2014====\nOn April 4, 2013, Fleming announced that he would not in 2014 seek the [[United States Senate]] held since 1997 by the Democratic [[Mary Landrieu]]. Instead his  colleague, U.S. Representative [[Bill Cassidy]] of [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge]], had announced on April 3 that he would challenge Landrieu. In his statement, Fleming said: \"For me to enter the race now would risk a contest between two experienced Republican congressmen, potentially offering Senator Landrieu a path back to Washington. I can't let that happen.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theadvocate.com/home/5618397-125/fleming-opts-out-of-landrieu|title=Jordan Blum, \"Fleming opts out of Landrieu challenge\", April 4, 2013|publisher=''[[The Advocate (Baton Rouge)|Baton Rouge Morning Advocate]]''|accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, Fleming endorsed Republican [[Louisiana State Senate|State Senator]] [[Neil Riser]] of [[Columbia, Louisiana|Columbia]] as his choice to succeed his retiring colleague Rodney Alexander of [[Jackson Parish, Louisiana|Jackson Parish]] in [[Louisiana's 5th congressional district]]. The [[special election]] to choose a successor to Alexander will be held on October 19.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theadvocate.com/home/6722936-125/us-rep-alexander-joining-jindal|title=Jordan Blum, Veterans job speeds D.C. exit|publisher=''Baton Rouge Morning Advocate'', August 7, 2013|accessdate=August 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn December 10, 2014, [[KTBS-TV|KTBS]], a [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]] based [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television station, reported that Fleming was considering running for the Senate seat held by [[David Vitter]], who ran in the  [[Louisiana gubernatorial election, 2015|2015 gubernatorial election]]. Vitter would have had to vacate his seat were he elected as [[Governor of Louisiana|governor]]. In a statement, Fleming said \"If Senator Vitter is elected as Governor, I would certainly be interested in running for the seat he would vacate.\"<ref name=\"Fleming Senate\">{{cite news|title=Fleming eyes U.S. Senate seat|url=http://www.ktbs.com/story/27600429/fleming-eyes-us-senate-seat|accessdate=24 December 2014|work=[[KTBS-TV|KTBS.com]]|date=10 December 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224034807/http://www.ktbs.com/story/27600429/fleming-eyes-us-senate-seat|archivedate=December 24, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n====2016====\n{{See also|United States Senate election in Louisiana, 2016}}\n\nOn December 7, 2015, Fleming officially announced his candidacy for the United States Senate.<ref name=\"senate race\">{{cite web|last1=deslatte|first1=melinda|title=Rep. Fleming Officially Announces for Louisiana Senate Race|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/rep-fleming-officially-announces-louisiana-senate-race-35627211|website=ABC NEWS|publisher=associated press|accessdate=7 December 2015}}</ref> He is a candidate to succeed fellow Republican [[David Vitter]], who will not seek a third term in 2016. Vitter lost the gubernatorial runoff election on November 21, 2015, to the Democrat [[John Bel Edwards]]. Others who sought the Senate seat that Vitter vacated were Fleming's House colleague and fellow physician, [[Charles Boustany]] of [[Lafayette, Louisiana|Lafayette]], Colonel Rob Maness of [[Madisonville, Louisiana|Madisonville]] in [[St. Tammany Parish]], a favorite of the [[Tea Party movement]] who ran against the defeated [[Mary Landrieu]] and the victorious [[Bill Cassidy]] in the race for Louisiana's other Senate seat in 2014, former [[Ku Klux Klan]] leader [[David Duke]], [[Foster Campbell]] of [[Bossier Parish, Louisiana|Bossier Parish]], a Democratic member of the [[Louisiana Public Service Commission]] and an advisor to John Bel Edwards, Democrat [[Caroline Fayard]], and [[State Treasurer]] [[John Neely Kennedy]] of Madisonville, the ultimate winner of the position.\n\n\"I not only fought the [[Liberal (politics)|liberals]] in Washington, I also fought the leadership of my own party when they were all too willing to compromise on our conservative principles,\" Fleming said in his statement of candidacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shreveporttimes.com/story/news/2015/12/07/rep-fleming-officially-enters-louisiana-senate-race/76941138/|title=Rep. Fleming officially enters Louisiana Senate race|publisher=''The Shreveport Times''|author=Deborah Barfield Berry|date=December 7, 2015|accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFleming finished in fifth place in the primary election with 204,026 votes (11 percent), just behind the Democrat Caroline Fayard, who drew 12 percent of the ballots cast. He amassed pluralities in seven parishes, six of which are in his House district: Bossier, [[Claiborne Parish, Louisiana|Claiborne]], [[Grant Parish, Louisiana|Grant]], [[Lincoln Parish, Louisiana|Lincoln]] ([[Louisiana's 5th congressional district]]), [[Sabine Parish, Louisiana|Sabine]], Webster, and [[Vernon Parish, Louisiana|Vernon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://voterportal.sos.la.gov/Graphical|title=Election Results|date=November 8, 2016|publisher=Louisiana Secretary of State|accessdate=December 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n\n====2011 tax plan comments====\nIn a September 19, 2011 interview on [[MSNBC]], in which Fleming criticized President Obama's proposed plan to increase taxes on the wealthy, Fleming told host [[Chris Jansing]], \"The amount that I have to invest in my business and feed my family is more like $600,000 of that $6.3 million.... So by the time I feed my family I have, maybe, $400,000 left over to invest in new locations, upgrade my locations, buy more equipment.\" When Jansing asked Fleming if he thought the \"average person\" might be unsympathetic to Fleming's position, Fleming responded, \"Class warfare never created a job...This is not about attacking people who make certain incomes. You know in this country, most people feel that being successful in their business is a virtue, not a vice, and once we begin to identify it as a vice, this country is going down.\"<ref name=\"alpert\">Alpert, Bruce. [http://www.nola.com/politics/index.ssf/2011/09/rep_john_fleming_of_louisiana.html \"Rep. John Fleming of Louisiana catches flak for income remarks.\"] ''The Times-Picayune'', 2011-09-20.</ref>\n\nFleming's remarks were widely reported and resulted in considerable commentary. Bruce Alpert, of Louisiana newspaper ''[[The Times-Picayune]],'' reported that \"on liberal blogs, Fleming was portrayed as insensitive to millions of working Americans who are struggling to meet expenses in the face of high unemployment and stagnant wages.\" <ref name=\"alpert\"/> Conservative sources including [[Bill O'Reilly (political commentator)|Bill O'Reilly]] and the [[Drudge Report]] defended Fleming's remarks; Josh Beavers, publisher of the ''[[Minden Press-Herald]]'' in Fleming's hometown, wrote an editorial which stated, \"[Fleming's] sentiment was only that the more taxes he pays the fewer people he can employ. High taxes on business owners thwart economic activity.\"<ref name=\"alpert\"/><ref>''The O'Reilly Factor''. Fox News. 2011-09-22. [http://www.foxnews.com/on-air/oreilly/2011/09/23/bill-oreilly-hits-back-jon-stewart#ixzz1Z5bGvPQJ Transcript.]</ref><ref>Beavers, Josh. [http://www.press-herald.com/index.php/opinion/josh-beavers/1323-congressman-fleming-said-nothing-wrong \"Congressman Fleming Said Nothing Wrong.\"] ''Minden Press-Herald'', 2011-09-21.</ref>\n\n====2013 budget cuts statement====\nIn 2013, Fleming was quoted in ''[[Forbes]]'' as saying:\"Republicans in general, we desperately want a reduction in spending to get government back into balance.  We would rather take some cuts in areas that we are not comfortable with than have no cuts at all.\"<ref name=Forbes>{{cite news|url=http://www.forbes.com/sites/lorenthompson/2013/02/04/republicans-target-their-own-voters-in-defense-budget-switch/ Forbes magazine website|work=Forbes|title=Republicans Target Their Own Voters In Defense Budget Switch|last=Thompson|first=Loren|date=February 4, 2013|accessdate=March 6, 2013}}</ref>  ''Forbes'' noted that Fleming's district includes [[Barksdale Air Force Base]] and [[Fort Polk]], both major employers.<ref name=Forbes /> At a discussion in February 2013 in [[DeRidder, Louisiana|DeRidder]], Fleming stated he would not vote to allow the government to cut $600 million from the defense plan.<ref>[http://www.beauregarddailynews.net/article/20130221/NEWS/130229892?refresh=true Fleming speaks about budget, Fort Polk at town hall meeting \u2013 News \u2013 Beauregard Daily News \u2013 Beauregard, LA<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\nFleming voted against the [[Budget Control Act of 2011]],<ref>{{USHVote|2011|690}}</ref> the act which caused the automatic budget sequestration in March 2013.\nIn this November 21, 2011 statement Fleming criticized the Budget Control Act because of what he called \"devastating cuts to military spending.\" <ref>[http://fleming.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=270058 Fleming Responds to Failure of Debt Reduction Committee | Congressman John Fleming<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n====Health care====\nIn September 2013, Fleming cosponsored and introduced the [[Republican Study Committee]]'s American Health Care Reform Act, which would repeal the soon-to-be-implemented [[Affordable Care Act]], which Fleming said was \"not fixable or repairable.\"<ref name=\"National Journal\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/daily/republican-alternative-to-obamacare-relies-on-repeal-20130922|title=Republican Alternative to Obamacare Relies on Repeal|work=National Journal|date=2013-09-22|accessdate=2013-11-20}}</ref>\n\nFleming's \"harsh criticism of the Affordable Care Act\" has drawn media attention.<ref name=\"Alpert\">Bruce Alpert, [http://www.nola.com/politics/index.ssf/2013/10/rep_fleming_gets_attention_for.html Rep. Fleming gets attention for calling Obamacare 'most dangerous law ever passed by Congress'], ''[[The Times-Picayune]]'' (October 28, 2013).</ref> In 2013, Fleming called the act \"the most dangerous piece of legislation ever passed in Congress.\"<ref name=\"Alpert\"/>\n\n====Religious Liberty/LGBT issues====\nIn 2012, Fleming condemned a private religious ceremony that took place at [[Fort Polk, Louisiana]], between an enlisted woman and civilian woman. (Fort Polk, a [[U.S. Army base]], lies within Fleming's congressional district.) Fleming said that the ceremony \"should not have occurred at Fort Polk, especially since the people of Louisiana have made it abundantly clear that our state does not recognize same-sex marriages or civil unions\" and characterized the event as part of a \"liberal social experiment with our military.\"<ref>Alan Duke, [http://www.cnn.com/2012/06/07/us/army-same-sex-ceremony/ Same-sex ceremony on Army post draws fire], CNN (June 7, 2012).</ref>\n\nFleming condemned the Supreme Court's 2015 decision in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'', which found a constitutional right to [[Same-sex marriage in the United States|same-sex marriage]].  Fleming stated that he was \"greatly disappointed\" and disagreed with the decision.<ref>Bruce Alpert, [http://www.nola.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/06/louisiana_gop_congressional_me.html  Louisiana GOP congressional members condemn ruling for gay marriage, Democrats say it advances freedom],  ''[[The Times-Picayune]]'' (June 26, 2015).</ref>\n\n====2013 military issues====\nIn June 2013, Fleming sponsored an amendment to a Defense spending bill requiring the military to accommodate, except in cases of military necessity, \"actions and speech\" reflecting the \"conscience, moral principles, or religious beliefs of the member.\" The amendment drew objections from the White House, with a spokesman saying that commanders need discretion to, \"address potentially problematic speech and actions within their units\" and that the measure would \"have a significant adverse effect on good order, discipline, morale and mission accomplishment.\" The amendment was approved by the House Armed Services Committee, and a companion measure passed in the Senate.<ref name=www.NOLA.com>{{cite news|url=http://www.nola.com/politics/index.ssf/2013/06/fleming_proposal_to_require_fr.html/|title=Fleming proposal to require free religious expression in military draws White House objections|publisher=The Times-Picayune|date=2013-06-12}}</ref> The amendment was criticised as allowing service members to harass gay colleagues.<ref>http://www.washingtonblade.com/2013/06/12/fleming-defends-anti-gay-conscience-amendment/</ref> Fleming's amendment was subsequently stripped from the final version of the bill.<ref>http://www.huffingtonpost.com/chris-rodda/rep-fleming-ndaa-religiou_b_4461318.html</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, the U.S. House passed a measure\u2014sponsored by Fleming\u2014that bars the Defense Department from appointing atheist chaplains. Fleming said, \"The notion of an atheist chaplain is nonsensical; it's an oxymoron.\" Democratic Congressman [[Rob Andrews]] of New Jersey said that it was \"wrong\" to tell an [[Irreligion|irreligious]] service member that they \"must go to a mental health professional in order to receive counseling, rather than someone who comes from their philosophical faith or tradition.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nola.com/politics/index.ssf/2013/07/house_passes_fleming_measure_t.html|title=House passes Rep. John Fleming\u2019s measure to ban atheist military chaplains|work=The Times-Picayune|date=2013-07-24}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nUpon his election to the [[United States House of Representatives]], Fleming was assigned to these committees:\n* [[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]],\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces]]\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Strategic Forces|Subcommittee on Strategic Forces]];\n* [[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]],\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources|Subcommittee on Energy and Mineral Resources]]\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Fisheries, Wildlife, Oceans and Insular Affairs|Subcommittee on Fisheries, Wildlife, Oceans and Insular Affairs]] (Chairman)\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* The [[Republican Study Committee]]\n* The [[Tea Party Caucus]]\n* Co-chair of the [[Addiction, Treatment and Recovery Caucus|Congressional Addiction, Treatment and Recovery Caucus]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Physicians in US Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Portalbar|Biography|Mississippi|South Carolina|California|Louisiana|United States Navy|Medicine|Business and Economics|Books|Politics|Conservatism|Government of the United States|Baptist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://fleming.house.gov/ Congressman John Fleming] official U.S. House site\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Louisiana/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/John_Fleming_%5BR-4%5D|John Fleming}}\n* {{C-SPAN|1031345}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = F000456 | ballot = John_Fleming | nndb = 600/000180060 | votesmart = 108811 | govtrack = 412275 | opencong = 412275 | rollcall = 29703 | politifact = john-fleming | fec = H8LA04225 | opensecrets = N00029679 | assets = john-fleming | legistorm = 953/Rep_John_C_Fleming.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = House/John_Fleming.htm | congress = john-fleming/1924 | worldcat = lccn-n2007-33236 | cspan = 1031345 | imdb = | bloomberg = john-fleming | nyt = | washpo = gIQARR2pAP }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim McCrery]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Louisiana|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Louisiana's 4th congressional district]]|years=2009\u2013present}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mike Johnson (Louisiana politician)|Mike Johnson]]<br><small>Elect</small>}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gerry Connolly]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=196th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Brett Guthrie]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{LA-FedRep}}\n{{LARepresentatives}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fleming, John C.}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:American coroners]]\n[[Category:American family and parenting writers]]\n[[Category:American health care businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American military physicians]]\n[[Category:American physicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Louisiana Republicans]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Charleston, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:People from Long Beach, California]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Meridian, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Minden, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives